<div xmlns:java="http://xml.apache.org/xslt/java" id="centre_col"><!-- begin original content --><h1>ESSUM35900 - Requirements relating
to share options - exercise rights: Sale (transfer) of a business
or company</h1>
<br>
<p>Paragraph 34 (5) (a) covers a scheme related employment that
ceases because the office or employment is in a company of which
the scheme organiser ceases to have control. The transfer of such
an employment out of the group still leaves the option-holder
employed by the same company. All that has changed is that the
employing company is now in another group or under the control of
another person. This does not amount to "redundancy" within the
Employment Protection Act.
<br>
<br> Paragraph 34 (5) (b) covers a scheme related employment that
ceases because the business or part of the business in which the
option-holder works is transferred by his employing company to
another person (other than an associated company of the scheme
organiser or a company under the control of that company). In these

circumstances the employer does change and the option-holder

becomes an employee of the person who acquired the business from

his former-employer. Such a cessation of employment can fall within

the definition of "redundancy" in the Employment Rights Act 1996,

and so also give a right of early exercise under paragraph 34 (2)

which may have more favourable tax consequences - see 

<a href="ESSUM35620.htm">ESSUM35620</a>.

<br>
<br> There is no substantive difference - at least as far as the

employees are concerned - between the sale of a company and the

sale of that company's business. But the method selected will often

make a difference to whether the employees have rights to exercise

their options and/or to the taxation consequences of doing so:</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">the sale of a business by a company, and

the resulting transfer of the employees employments constitutes

"redundancy" within the meaning of the Transfer of Undertakings

(Protection of Employment) Regulations 2006 (Chapman &amp; Elkin v

CPS Computer Group 1987 Industrial Law Reports 462)</li>
<li class="filledcircle">the transfer of a company out of a group

does not constitute redundancy for that company's employees. The

employees remain employed by the same company throughout (Thompson

v Asda-MFI Group plc, 1988 2All ER 722). In the Asda case the terms

of the share options were such that if the option- holders ceased

to be employed in Asda's group their options lapsed. The court

rejected the contention by the employees that Asda could not be

allowed by its own act - the sale of its subsidiary, Wades

Departmental Stores Ltd - to destroy the contractual rights it had

created.</li>
</ul>
